The locust years of Latin America
Bad news continue to pile up in Latin America these days.
Economic conditions are worsening almost everywhere, social cohesion is eroding, and political instability is growing.
This is not surprising given that the vast majority of Latin American countries have spent the last twenty years going nowhere.
Capital has been sold off and national debts have skyrocketed, but nothing lasting and beneficial has been achieved.
These years have really been devastated by locusts.
Over the last 20 years, annual per capita GDP growth in Latin America has averaged 0.35%.
At this rate, an economy would take 200 years to double.
In Asia, living standards double every decade.
With such anemic growth, how can Latin America hope to compete in the global trade arena except through a still meager increase in wages?
The economic stagnation is due to poor governance, not bad luck.
If Latin America does not change, it may start resembling Africa more and more - a region composed of weak states with large informal economies and widespread poverty.
Four factors have placed it on this path.
Firstly, in the rush towards privatization, everything from public services to manufacturing industries was sold off at auction.
For a brief moment, capital sales helped balance national budgets and also provided resources to support consumption.
Finally, revenues from privatization have produced little in terms of better infrastructure or more competitive exports.
Worse still, the liquidation of state assets was accompanied by massive external borrowing.
In some cases, particularly in Argentina, the borrowing done by national buyers depleted all available credit lines.
Other countries may not have reached Argentina's level, but solvency is a problem almost everywhere in Latin America.
Secondly, since reform has not brought prosperity, the region has become disillusioned with it.
The inflow of capital produced a wealth effect, but only as long as it existed.
When the money stopped flowing, the wealth dried up.
No sensible politician would commit to another decade of structural reforms that would push the patience of average Latin Americans beyond the limits of electoral survival.
But without a greater number of deep reforms, too few preconditions for economic growth will be met to attract investments, without which no growth is possible.
This development dilemma signals the third factor: incompetent policies.
The governments that followed technocratic lines and saw economic growth as a rising tide lifting all boats have disappeared.
In Argentina, clumsy presidents keep succeeding each other.
Institutions are being dismantled, property rights are being questioned, and a random and even more corrupt redistribution effort is underway.
Peru and Venezuela are not much better off; Brazil may soon follow the same path.
The popularity of Luiz Inácio da Silva and his team, who lead opinion polls ahead of Brazil's presidential elections, indicates that a large part of the Latin American population is ready to reject traditional governments.
Lula and his party are so far from the dominant economic and political thinking that capital has already begun to flee – even though elections are still several months away.
In Mexico, democratization has brought greater stability, but this could well prove ephemeral.
The peso is now excessively overvalued.
If the external balance deteriorates further, the economy risks landing hard.
Regarding all the good news about Mexico's nascent democracy, its president is starting to justify the fears that existed about him: no vision, no Congress, and no team knowing what to do.
The last factor concerns the desperately low savings rate that is endemic to the Americas.
In fact, this is the economically speaking financial result because where there is little savings, there is little investment - and little basis for accumulating capital and increasing productivity.
Venezuela now longs for the fat years of the 1970s of OPEC – to which it did not participate, having neglected to develop its oil industry.
Argentina’s wealth is now taking vacations in Miami, perhaps forever.
Brazil and Mexico are perfect examples of countries that sold their assets and borrowed rather than saved.
The contrast with Asia is striking.
Take China, where savings and investment rates reach nearly 40%, where the current account is in surplus, and where there is no public debt.
Government institutions favor the market, and the population is well-educated, disciplined, and flexible in learning.
Rewards for risk-taking and initiative are immediate and strongly motivating.
We cannot deny that China remains a poor country.
Its per capita GDP represents only half of Brazil's.
But with annual growth in China's coastal region at about 15%, who can seriously doubt that it will surpass Brazil in the next 15 years?
In China, despite all the huge problems encountered, things continue to proceed correctly, primarily due to the massive flow of foreign direct investment and the imminent benefits of joining the WTO.
In Latin America, things continue to deteriorate: governments backtrack on reform, and the economy loses ground against the rest of the world.
Latin America was doing well when unregulated funds flowed in, but those times are largely over.
We must therefore expect much worse economic, social, and political conditions in the years ahead.
Demagogues such as Hugo Chavez in Venezuela or Carlos Menem – another Argentine presidential candidate once again – may seem like a bad joke, but anyone concerned about the fate of Latin America should not laugh at them.
